NATION BRIEFS																																												 Kumbakonam, Nov. 28 (PTI): Actress Kushboo is in trouble again  this time for wearing chappals in front of idols of goddesses at a film mahurat in Chennai recently.																																												Gurumurthy, a Hindu Munnani activist, lodged a complaint against the actress before a civil court here today accusing her of hurting religious sentiments. The case has been posted for hearing on December 3.																																												Chennai (PTI): Madras High Court has issued notices to the states health department, medical council and Tamil Nadu chemists and druggists association to prevent misuse of the Red Cross emblem by medical practitioners, pharmacists, hospitals and other allied fields. The bench was hearing a PIL seeking to direct the state government to prevent misuse of the emblem.																																												Chennai (PTI): Singapore Airlines has obtained exclusive rights for the in-flight screening of Tamil superstar Rajnikanths blockbuster Sivaji-The Boss. This is the first time that the airline has purchased the rights of an Indian movie.																																												Kochi (PTI): Abraham Puthussery, a former Congressman, has made it to the Limca Book of National Records by collecting articles and photographs of himself published in newspapers since 1948. His 480-pages album containing over 2,000 reports and photographs weighs 4.5 kg.																																												 Panaji (PTI): At least 2,000 DVDs of four short films on HIV-AIDS have been prepared for MPs to help them spread awareness under project AIDS Jaago. The DVDs were prepared in collaboration with Mirabai Films, headed by Mira Nair, and the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation. Mira Nair, Farhan Akhtar, Vishal Bharadwaj and Santosh Sivan made the films.																																												Nashik (PTI): Dacoits looted a jewellery shop of gold and silver ornaments worth over Rs 22 lakhs while police were busy with President Pratibha Patils visit.
